se-attack-idUSKBN1ZD1ZZ|work=Reuters|title=Islamic State claims responsibility for Niger army base attack|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 10]] \u2013 The [[Sultan of Oman]], [[Qaboos bin Said]], dies aged 79. [[Haitham bin Tariq]] is sworn in as his successor.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50902476|title= Sultan Qaboos of Oman dies aged 79|date = January 11, 2020|accessdate = January 11, 2020|work = [[BBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2020/01/oman-sultan-qaboos-dies-oman-state-media-200111000944539.html|title= Oman's Sultan Qaboos dies: state media|date = January 11, 2020|accessdate = January 10, 2020|work = [[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Oman's new ruler Haitham bin Tariq takes oath: newspapers |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oman-sultan-successor-media/omans-new-ruler-haitham-bin-tariq-takes-oath-newspapers-idUSKCN1ZA078 |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |work=Reuters |date=January 11, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[January 18]] \u2013 [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]]: 111 Yemeni soldiers and five civilians are killed in a [[2020 Ma'rib attack|drone and missile attack]] on a [[military camp]] near [[Ma'rib]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51166943|title=Yemen war: Death toll in attack on military base rises to 111|date=January 20, 2020 |access-date=January 20, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n* [[January 28]] \u2013 [[President of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]] and Prime Minister of [[Israel]] [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] announce the [[Trump peace plan]].\n* [[January 29]] \u2013 U.S. President Donald Trump signs the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]], the North American trade agreement replacing [[NAFTA]].<ref>{{cite web|website=BBC News|title=Trump signs US Mexico Canada Agreement|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51300625|date=Jan 29, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 30]] \u2013 [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]: The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declares the outbreak of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|the disease]] as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]], the sixth time that this measure has been invoked since 2009.<ref name=\"WHODeclaration\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51318246 |title=Coronavirus declared global health emergency |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=January 30, 2020 |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=January 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130201004/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51318246 |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/01/30/who-declares-coronavirus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency/|title=WHO declares coronavirus pandemic a global health emergency|author=Joseph, Andrew |date=January 30, 2020 |publisher=[[Stat News]] |access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/world/asia/coronavirus-china.html/|title=Coronavirus Live Updates: W.H.O. Declares a Global Health Emergency|date=January 30, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=January 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130061033/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/world/asia/coronavirus-china.html|archive-date=January 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[January 31]] \u2013 The [[United Kingdom]] and [[Gibraltar]] formally withdraw from the [[European Union]] at 11PM (GMT), beginning an 11-month [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|transition period]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51287430 | title=European Parliament approves Brexit agreement| work=BBC News| date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* [[February 11]] \u2013 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) names the disease [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-51466362|title=Coronavirus disease named Covid-19|website=BBC|accessdate=February 11, 2020|date=February 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/wuhan-virus-coronavirus-who-new-name-12424116|title=Novel coronavirus to be called COVID-19, says WHO|website=CNA|accessdate=February 11, 2020|date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[February 13]] \u2013 [[NASA]] publishes a detailed study of [[486958 Arrokoth|Arrokoth]], the most distant body ever explored by a spacecraft, which ''[[New Horizons]]'' passed by on its journey through the [[Kuiper belt]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Not just a space potato': Nasa unveils 'astonishing' details of most distant object ever visited |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/feb/13/not-just-a-space-potato-nasa-unveils-astonishing-details-of-most-distant-object-ever-visited-arrokoth |date=February 13, 2020 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= The Most Distant World We've Ever Explored Just Shed Light on How Planets Are Born |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/here-s-what-arrokoth-can-tell-us-about-how-baby-planets-are-born |date=February 13, 2020 |work=Science Alert |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The solar nebula origin of (486958) Arrokoth, a primordial contact binary in the Kuiper Belt |url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/02/12/science.aay6620 |date=13 February 2020 |work=Science |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[February 27]] \u2013 [[2020 stock market crash]]: The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] (DJIA) plunges by 1,190.95 points, or 4.4%, to close at 25,766.64, its largest one-day points decline at the time. This follows several days of large falls, marking the worst week for the index since [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008]], triggered by fears of the spreading [[socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Dow plunges 1,100 points as the coronavirus sends the market tumbling into correction territory|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/26/dow-futures-fall-after-microsoft-issues-coronavirus-warning.html|publisher=CNBC |date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[February 28]] \u2013 Ambassadors of all 29 [[NATO]] Allies meet in the [[North Atlantic Council]] expressing solidarity with [[Turkey]] after 33 Turkish soldiers were killed in an [[2020 Balyun airstrikes|airstrike]] by pro-Syrian government forces during the ongoing [[Syrian civil war]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51667717 Syria war: Alarm after 33 Turkish soldiers killed in attack in Idlib - BBC News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/28/nato-turkey-syria-airstrikes-russia-un-jens-stoltenberg Nato expresses 'full solidarity' with Turkey over Syria airstrikes | World news | The Guardian<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_173927.htm |title = NATO expresses strong solidarity with Turkey at special meeting of the North Atlantic Council}}</ref>\n* [[February 29]] \u2013 A [[Afghan peace process#2020 agreement|conditional peace agreement]] is signed between the United States and the [[Taliban]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].<ref>{{cite web |title=US, Taliban truce takes effect, setting stage for peace deal |url=https://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/national-politics/us-taliban-truce-takes-effect-setting-stage-for-peace-deal |website=The Denver Channel |date=February 21, 2020 |publisher=The Denver Channel |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The U.S. begins gradually [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan#Plans by the administration of Donald Trump|withdrawing troops]] from [[Afghanistan]] on March 10.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51810498|work=BBC|title=Afghanistan conflict: US begins withdrawing troops|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* [[March 5]] \u2013 The [[International Criminal Court]] authorizes the [[Alleged United States War Crimes#War on Terror|Afghanistan War Crimes]] inquiry to proceed, allowing for the first time for [[Citizenship of the United States|U.S. forces]] to be investigated.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peltier|first=Elian|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/world/europe/afghanistan-war-crimes-icc.html|title=I.C.C. Allows Afghanistan War Crimes Inquiry to Proceed, Angering U.S.|date=March 5, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 6, 2020|last2=Faizi|first2=Fatima|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* [[March 8]] \u2013 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: [[Italy]] places 16 million people in [[quarantine]], more than a quarter of its population, in a bid to stop the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/08/coronavirus-italy-quarantine-virus-reaches-washington-dc|title=Coronavirus: quarter of Italy's population put in quarantine as virus reaches Washington DC|website=The Guardian|language=en|date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> Two days later, the quarantine is [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|expanded]] to cover the entire country.\n* [[March 9]] \u2013 [[2020 stock market crash#Black Monday I (9 March 2020)|Share prices fall sharply]] around the world, in response to [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|a new oil price war]] and the [[Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|impact of COVID-19]]. The DJIA plunges more than 2,000 points, the largest fall in its history up to that point.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51796806|title=Black Monday: Shares face biggest fall since financial crisis|website=BBC News|language=en|date=March 9, 2020|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> [[Oil prices]] also plunge by as much as 30 percent in early trading, the biggest fall since [[1990 oil price shock|1991]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Oil prices plunge as much as 30% after OPEC deal failure sparks price war |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/08/oil-plummets-30percent-as-opec-deal-failure-sparks-price-war-fears.html |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |agency=CNBC}}</ref>\n* [[March 11]]\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The [[World Health Organization]] declares the COVID-19 outbreak a [[pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-51839944|title=Coronavirus confirmed as pandemic by World Health Organization|website=BBC News|language=en|date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Elizabeth II]] becomes the [[list of longest-reigning monarchs|longest-reigning monarch]] in the Americas, surpassing [[K\u02bcinich Janaab\u02bc Pakal|Pacal the Great]], who held that record for almost 1337 years, from 683 to 2020.\n* [[March 12]] \u2013 [[2020 stock market crash#Black Thursday (12 March 2020)|Global stock markets crash]] due to continued concerns over COVID-19 and the U.S. [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Europe 2|travel ban]] on the [[Schengen Area]]. The Dow Jones Industrial Average goes into free fall, closing at over -2,300 points, the worst losses for the index since [[Black Monday (1987)|1987]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wearden (earlier)|first=Graeme|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live|title=Wall Street and FTSE 100 plunge on worst day since 1987 \u2013 as it happened|date=March 12, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 13, 2020|last2=Jolly (now)|first2=Jasper|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* [[March 13]] \u2013 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The [[government of Nepal]] announces that [[Mount Everest]] will be closed to climbers and the public for the rest of the season due to concerns from the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/mount-everest-coronavirus-closed-scli-intl/index.html|title=Mount Everest closed over coronavirus fears|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[March 14]] \u2013 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: [[Spain]] goes into [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|lockdown]] after COVID-19 cases in the country surge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/coronavirus-spain-nationwide-lockdown/2020/03/14/3bec8690-6619-11ea-8a8e-5c5336b32760_story.html|title=Spain goes on nationwide lockdown as coronavirus cases surge|date=March 14, 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=March 14, 2020|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* [[March 15]] \u2013 Argentine president [[Alberto Fern\u00e1ndez]] declares preventive [[quarantine]] to gradual [[lockdown]] of the country being the first country aside from Spain and Italy to lockdown the country and the first one after few cases and no deaths were confirmed.\n* [[March 16]] \u2013 The DJIA [[2020 stock market crash#Black Monday II (16 March 2020)|falls by \u20132,997.10]], the single [[List of largest daily changes in the Dow Jones Industrial Average|largest point drop in history]] and the second largest percentage drop ever at \u221212.93 percent, an even greater crash than [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|Black Monday (1929)]]. This follows the U.S. [[Federal Reserve]] announcing that it will cut its target interest rate to 0 to 1/4 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/monetary20200315a.htm|title=Federal Reserve issues FOMC statement|website=Federal Reserve|date=March 15, 2020|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[March 17]]\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iranian government]] warns that \"millions\" of its citizens may die from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|COVID-19]] as 988 people have thus far died in the country. 90 percent of the 18,000 COVID-19 cases in the [[Middle East]] have thus far occurred in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|website=AP |title=Iran warns virus could kill 'millions' in Islamic Republic|author1=NASSER KARIMI|author2=JON GAMBRELL|date=March 17, 2020 |url=https://apnews.com/6e92d93551ee6c6ae51d0acaaad9eb32}}</ref>\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: European leaders close the [[European Union|EU]]'s external and Schengen borders for at least 30 days in an effort to curb the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/coronavirus/linksdossier/coronavirus-whats-happening-in-europe/|title=Coronavirus: What's happening in Europe|website=Euractiv|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: [[UEFA]] postpones the [[Euro 2020]] [[association football]] tournament until summer 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/19692/11958779/euro-2020-postponed-until-summer-of-2021-following-coronavirus-pandemic|title=Euro 2020 postponed until summer 2021; domestic leagues, UEFA competitions to be completed by June 30|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The next day, the [[European Broadcasting Union]] announces that the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] will be cancelled due to COVID-19 in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Europe]], the first cancellation in the 64-year history of the contest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation|title=Eurovision 2020 cancellation for the first time in history of the contest.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [[March 20]] \u2013 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The worldwide death toll from COVID-19 surpasses 10,000 as the total number of cases reaches a quarter of a million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-51969508|title=Global coronavirus deaths pass 10,000|website=BBC News|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[March 23]] \u2013 Ten nations had joined the SOLIDARITY trial, a group sponsored by the [[World Health Organization]] to find a cure against COVID-19. Four European countries ([[Switzerland]], [[France]], [[Norway]] and [[Spain]]), two American countries ([[Argentina]] and [[Canada]]), three Asian countries ([[Iran]], [[Thailand]], [[Bahrain]]) and [[South Africa]] are leading efforts to finding a cure.\n* [[March 24]]\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: [[India]] goes into [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|lockdown]] for 21 days to contain COVID-19. The total number of people in the world facing some form of movement restriction now exceeds 2.6 billion, a third of the global population.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/britain-lockdown-warns-pandemic-accelerating-051357601.html|work=Yahoo! News|title=A third of the world under virus lockdown, as Olympics delayed|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-52024239|work=BBC News|title=Coronavirus: India enters 'total lockdown' after spike in cases|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The United Kingdom goes into [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|lockdown]] for three weeks to contain COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.K. government imposes 3-week national lockdown, enforced by police, to contain coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/uk-government-imposes-3-week-national-lockdown-enforced-police-contain-n1167141 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Premier]] [[Li Keqiang]] reports that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|domestically transmitted epidemic]] was \"basically blocked\" and the domestic outbreak was now controlled.<ref>{{cite news |title= China deploys measures to curb imported COVID-19 cases, rebound in indigenous cases |url= http://english.scio.gov.cn/m/topnews/2020-03/24/content_75852078.htm |work=State Council Information Office of China |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Two days later, China temporarily suspends entry for foreign nationals with [[Travel visa|visas]] or [[residence permit]]s, effective midnight March 28.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.axios.com/china-foreigners-visas-coronavirus-6e87eea9-73f3-4342-aee2-a171ca742ea5.html|work=Axios|date=March 26, 2020|title=China to temporarily bar entry of foreigners to stop spread of coronavirus}}</ref>\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The [[International Olympic Committee]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan|Japan]] suspend the [[2020 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] until [[2021]], without a rescheduled date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/24/tokyo-olympics-to-be-postponed-to-2021-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic|title=Tokyo Olympics postponed to 2021 due to coronavirus pandemic|website=The Guardian|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[March 26]]\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: Global COVID-19 cases reach 500,000, with nearly 23,000 deaths confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/carlieporterfield/2020/03/26/500000-coronavirus-cases-reported-worldwide/#63ddd34c59b8|title=500,000 Coronavirus Cases Reported Worldwide|work=Forbes|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The United States surpasses China and Italy in total number of known COVID-19 cases, with at least 81,321 cases and more than 1,000 deaths.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/the-us-now-leads-the-world-in-confirmed-coronavirus-cases/ar-BB11LlDh|title=The U.S. Now Leads the World in Confirmed Coronavirus Cases|work=The New York Times|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: Militants in [[Abu Sayyaf|the Philippines]], Syria, [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemen]], and Libya agree to U.N. Secretary-General [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres|Ant\u00f3nio Guterres's]] call for a ceasefire; some accept medical aid for themselves and the noncombatants in their communities. Guterres also asked wealthy countries to provide $2 billion to aid in fighting the virus. Colombia and Venezuela discussed a common response to the global pandemic, and the UAE airlifted aid to Iran.<ref>[https://www.csmonitor.com/Commentary/the-monitors-view/2020/0326/Trading-handguns-for-handwipes Trading handguns for handwipes] Christian Science Monitor, March 26, 2020</ref>\n** A third [[Coral bleaching|mass coral bleaching event]] in five years is recorded at the [[Great Barrier Reef]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-australia-52043554|title=Great Barrier Reef suffers third mass bleaching in five years|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/news-room/latest-news/latest-news/coral-bleaching/2020/statement-coral-bleaching-on-the-great-barrier-reef|title=Statement: coral bleaching on the Great Barrier Reef|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|work=GBRMPA}}</ref>\n* [[March 27]] \u2013 [[North Macedonia]] becomes the 30th country to join [[NATO]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.defensenews.com/global/europe/2020/03/24/north-macedonia-expected-to-join-nato-within-days/ |title=North Macedonia to officially join NATO on Friday |first=Aaron |last=Mehta |date=March 24, 2020 |website=Defense News}}</ref>\n* [[March 30]]\n** 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic: The number of deaths in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|Spain, 7,340]], surpasses those in China.<ref>[https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-spain-covid-19-deaths-rise-by-812-to-7-340-11965650 Coronavirus: Spain surpasses China COVID-19 cases as deaths rise to 7,340] by Alex Culbertson, Sky News, March 30, 2020</ref>\n** [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]]: The price of [[Brent Crude]] falls 9% to $23 per barrel, 