 20\u4e16\u7eaa\u7269\u7406\u5b66\u5de8\u4eba\u3001\u8bfa\u5956\u5f97\u4e3b\u83f2\u5229\u666e\u5b89\u5fb7\u68ee\u901d\u4e16\uff0c\u4eab\u5e7496\u5c81] {{in lang|zh}}</ref>\n** [[Yuri Bondarev]], Soviet and Russian writer and screenwriter (b. [[1924]])<ref>[https://tass.ru/kultura/8109675 \u0423\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u042e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432] {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n** [[Ken Shimura]], Japanese comedian (b. [[1950]])<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/30/world/asia/30reuters-health-coronavirus-japan-comedian.html/ Japanese Comedian Ken Shimura Dies From Coronavirus]</ref>\n** [[Krzysztof Penderecki]], Polish composer and conductor (b. [[1933]])<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-poland-music-penderecki/polish-composer-penderecki-dies-at-86-after-long-illness-idUSKBN21G08D/ Polish composer Penderecki dies at 86 after long illness]</ref>\n* [[March 30]]\n**[[Manolis Glezos]], Greek politician and resistance fighter (b. [[1922]])<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-greece-glezos/glezos-greek-who-tore-swastika-from-acropolis-in-ww2-dies-aged-97-idUSKBN21H1TO Glezos, Greek who tore swastika from Acropolis in WW2, dies aged 97]</ref>\n** [[Hau Pei-tsun]], 13th [[Premier of the Republic of China]] (b. [[1919]])<ref>[https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202003305012.aspx \u90dd\u67cf\u6751\u53bb\u4e16 \u4eab\u5d69\u58fd101\u6b72] {{in lang|zh}}</ref>\n** [[Joachim Yhombi-Opango]], 4th [[List of presidents of the Republic of the Congo|President]] and 12th [[List of prime ministers of the Republic of the Congo|Prime Minister of the Republic of the Congo]] (b. [[1939]])<ref>[https://www.lefigaro.fr/international/coronavirus-deces-de-l-ex-president-congolais-yhombi-opango-20200330 Coronavirus : d\u00e9c\u00e8s de l'ex-pr\u00e9sident congolais Yhombi Opango] {{in lang|fr}} </ref>\n* [[March 31]] \u2013 [[Abdul Halim Khaddam]], Acting [[President of Syria]] (b. [[1932]])<ref>[https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/former-syrian-vice-president-abdel-halim-khaddam-passes-away-in-france/ Former Syrian Vice President Abdel-Halim Khaddam passes away in France]</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n{{Main|Deaths in April 2020}}\n* [[April 1]] \n**[[Nur Hassan Hussein]], 12th [[Prime Minister of Somalia]] (b. [[1937]])<ref>[https://www.garoweonline.com/en/news/somalia/ex-somali-pm-dies-of-coronavirus-in-london Ex-Somali PM dies of Coronavirus in London]</ref>\n** [[Ellis Marsalis Jr.]], American jazz pianist (b. [[1934]])<ref>[https://www.nola.com/entertainment_life/music/article_bbdaf4c4-7481-11ea-92ae-1758b23c65c8.html New Orleans jazz piano legend Ellis Marsalis dies, city officials say]</ref>\n** [[Adam Schlesinger]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist (b. [[1967]])<ref>[https://variety.com/2020/music/obituaries-people-news/adam-schlesinger-coronavirus-dead-dies-1203552130/ Adam Schlesinger, Emmy Winner and Fountains of Wayne Cofounder, Dies of Coronavirus Complications]</ref>\n\n==In fiction==\n{{main|21st century in fiction#2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Wikinews|main page}}\n{{portal|Current events|Modern history}}\n\n[[Category:2020| ]]\n[[Category:Leap years in the Gregorian calendar]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history| ]]\n", "name_user": "NathanK3945", "label": "safe", "comment": "coronavirus 1 000 000 cases worldwide + source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020"}
{"title_page": "North Staffordshire Regiment", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name               = Prince of Wales's (North Staffordshire Regiment)<br>North Staffordshire Regiment (Prince of Wales's)\n| image                   = North Staffordshire Regiment Cap Badge.jpg\n| image_size              = 180px\n| caption                 = Regimental Cap Badge of the North Staffordshire Regiment\n| dates                   = 1881\u20131959\n| country                 = {{flagu|United Kingdom}}\n| allegiance              = \n| branch                  = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n| type                    = [[Infantry]]\n| role                    = [[Line infantry]]\n| size                    = \n| command_structure       = \n| current_commander       = \n| garrison                = [[Whittington Barracks]], [[Lichfield]]\n| ceremonial_chief        = \n| colonel_of_the_regiment = The Prince of Wales\n| nickname                = The Black Knots\n| patron                  = \n| motto                   = \n| colors                  = Maroon, black and silver\n| march                   = [[God Bless the Prince of Wales]] (slow march)<br>The Days We Went a'Gypsying (quick march)\n| mascot                  = \n| battles                 = \n| notable_commanders      = \n| anniversaries           = 31 July, [[Battle of Passchendaele|Third Battle of Ypres]]\n| disbanded               = 31 January 1959 \n}}\n{{quote box\n| width     = 315px\n| border    = 1px\n| align     = right\n| bgcolor   = \n| fontsize  = 85%\n| title_bg  = \n| title_fnt = \n| title     = \n| quote     = I have always thought that if one was prepared to take the rough with the smooth they would ultimately balance out, but this has not been the case with the North Staffordshire Regiment, who throughout their history, have had far too much of the rough and far too little of the smooth.\n| salign    = right\n| source    = [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] [[Sir]] [[Brian Horrocks]]{{sfn|Cook|1970|loc=Introduction}}\n}}\nThe '''North Staffordshire Regiment (Prince of Wales's)''' was a [[line infantry]] [[regiment]] of the [[British Army]], which was in existence between 1881 and 1959. The [[64th (2nd Staffordshire) Regiment of Foot]] was created on 21 April 1758 from the 2nd Battalion of the [[Devonshire Regiment|11th Regiment of Foot]].<ref name=LG31583/> In 1881, under the [[Childers Reforms]], the 64th Regiment of Foot was merged with the [[98th (Prince of Wales's) Regiment of Foot]] (originally raised in 1824) to form the '''Prince of Wales's (North Staffordshire Regiment)'''. In 1921 the regimental title was altered to the '''North Staffordshire Regiment (Prince of Wales's)'''.\n\nFormed at a time when the [[British Empire]] was reaching its peak, the regiment served all over the Empire, in times of both peace and war, and in many theatres of war outside the Empire. It fought with distinction in [[World War I]] and [[World War II]], as well as in other smaller conflicts around the world. These other wars included the [[Mahdist War#Return of the British|Second Sudanese War]], the [[Second Boer War]], the [[Irish War of Independence|Anglo-Irish War]] and the [[Third Anglo-Afghan War]].\n\nIn 1959, as part of a defence review, the North Staffordshire Regiment, by now reduced to only a single regular battalion, was amalgamated with the [[South Staffordshire Regiment]] to form the [[Staffordshire Regiment|Staffordshire Regiment (Prince of Wales's)]] which was, in 2006, amalgamated with the [[Cheshire Regiment]] and the [[Worcestershire and Sherwood Foresters Regiment|Worcestershire and Sherwood Foresters Regiment (29th/45th Foot)]] to form the [[Mercian Regiment]]. Today the traditions of the North Staffordshire Regiment are continued by the [[Mercian Regiment]].\n\n==Formation history==\n{{Main|64th (2nd Staffordshire) Regiment of Foot|98th (Prince of Wales's) Regiment of Foot}}\n\nThe '''Prince of Wales's (North Staffordshire) Regiment''' was formed under the [[Childers Reforms]] on 1 July 1881, by the amalgamation of the [[64th (2nd Staffordshire) Regiment of Foot]] and [[98th (Prince of Wales's) Regiment of Foot]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=62}} These two regular regiments became, respectively, the 1st and 2nd battalions of the new regiment.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=62}} The [[Militia (United Kingdom)|Militia]] and [[Volunteer Force (Great Britain)|Rifle Volunteers]] forces of North Staffordshire were also incorporated into this new regiment, and a permanent [[Regimental depot|depot]] was established at [[Whittington Barracks]], [[Lichfield]], which also housed the newly formed [[South Staffordshire Regiment]].{{sfn|The brief history of the Staffordshire Regiment, part 1|2010|p=3}}\n\nThe 64th Regiment of Foot was originally raised in 1756 as the 2nd Battalion of the [[Devonshire Regiment|11th (Devonshire) Foot]], and was renumbered the 64th in 1758. It had a long history of overseas service with much less time spent in Europe. It had served in the [[West Indies]] during the [[Seven Years' War]], America during the [[American War of Independence]], South America, the West Indies and Canada during the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. Subsequent long periods were spent in Ireland and the West Indies before action was seen in India during the [[Indian Mutiny]]. At the time of the forming of the amalgamation with the 98th Foot, the 64th was based in Ireland.{{sfn|Cook|1970|pp=127\u2013128}}\n\nThe 98th Regiment of Foot, raised in 1824 in [[Chichester]], had a much shorter history, but like the 64th had spent the majority of its time overseas spending a long time in South Africa before seeing action in China in the [[First Opium War|First Anglo-Chinese (or Opium) War]] and India on the [[North-West Frontier (military history)|North West Frontier]]. It was based in Afghanistan when the amalgamation occurred.{{sfn|Cook|1970|pp=127\u2013128}}\n\nThe battalions that constituted the regiment in 1881 were as follows:\n\n* 1st Battalion: the [[64th (2nd Staffordshire) Regiment of Foot]];\n* 2nd Battalion: the [[98th (Prince of Wales's) Regiment of Foot]];\n* 3rd (Militia) Battalion: The King's Own (2nd Staffordshire) Light Infantry Militia, based in [[Stafford]];\n* 4th (Militia) Battalion: The King's Own (3rd Staffordshire) Rifles Militia, based in [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]];\n* 1st Volunteer Battalion: 2nd Staffordshire ([[Staffordshire Rangers]]) Rifle Volunteer Corps, based in [[Stoke-on-Trent]];\n* 2nd Volunteer Battalion: 5th Staffordshire Rifle Volunteer Corps, based in Lichfield but later moved to [[Burton-on-Trent]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=62}}\n\n==Volunteers and Territorials==\nThe 2nd and 5th Staffordshire Rifle Volunteer Corps were designated the 1st and 2nd Volunteer battalions, North Staffordshire Regiment, in 1883. Together with the Volunteer battalions of the [[South Staffordshire Regiment]], they formed the [[Staffordshire Brigade|Staffordshire Volunteer Infantry Brigade]] in 1888. This brigade was intended to assemble at [[Wolverhampton]] in time of war, while in peacetime it acted as a focus for collective training of the Volunteers. On the formation of the [[Territorial Force]] in 1908, the two Volunteer battalions were renumbered as the 5th and 6th battalions of the North Staffordshire Regiment, forming part of the Staffordshire Brigade in the [[46th (North Midland) Division|North Midland Division]].{{sfn|Westlake|2010|pages=217\u201322}}{{sfn|Becke|2007|pages=61\u201367}}\n\nThe reserve battalions of the regiment were also reorganised in 1908 by the [[Territorial and Reserve Forces Act 1907]], with the two [[Militia (United Kingdom)|militia]] battalions being re-designated the 3rd (Special) and 4th (Special Reserve) battalions, and the volunteer battalions being re-designated as Territorial Force and renumbered as the 5th and 6th battalions (TF): they were based at [[College Road drill hall, Hanley|College Road]] in [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Hanley]] and [[Horninglow Street drill hall, Burton upon Trent|Horninglow Street]] in [[Burton upon Trent]] respectively.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=72}}\n\n==Early service (1881\u20131914)==\n\n===Garrison duties and the Mahdist War===\n[[File:North Staffordshire Regiment Officers.jpg|thumb|300px|Officers of the 2nd Battalion, India 1908]]\nThe 1st Battalion was stationed in Ireland at the time of the amalgamation. It moved to England in 1883, and the following year to the [[West Indies]], based mainly in [[Barbados]], but with detachments on other islands. It moved to [[Colony of Natal|Natal]] in 1887, to [[Mauritius]] in 1890, to [[Malta]] in 1893 and to [[Egypt]] in 1895. From there the 1st Battalion took part in operations in the [[Mahdist War#Return of the British|Second Sudanese War]] under [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|pp=67\u201371}} During the campaign, the 1st Battalion were based initially at [[Wadi Halfa]] but moved to [[Gemai]] to avoid a [[cholera]] outbreak. In September the battalion took part in the action against the [[Dervish]] Army at Hafir, which was decisive in ending the campaign. As a result, the North Staffordshire Regiment received the unique \"Hafir\" [[battle honour]], given to no other British regiment.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=71}}{{sfn|Rodger|2003|p=64}}\n\n===Second Boer War===\nThe 2nd Battalion was stationed in [[British Raj|India]] in 1881 when the North Staffordshire Regiment was formed, and remained there until 1886. During this time period, it took part in an expedition to the [[Zhob]] Valley in 1884, thus making it the first battalion in the regiment to see active service.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=62}} In 1886, it returned to England via [[Aden]], and then deployed to Ireland in 1893. In 1899, 2nd Battalion mobilised and moved to [[South Africa]], where it took part in the [[Second Boer War]]. Forming part of [[15th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|15th Brigade]] in the [[7th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|7th Division]],{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=73}} the majority of the battalion saw little action throughout the conflict, being mostly occupied in garrison duties in [[Johannesburg]] in 1900.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=75}} In 1901, the battalion was part of a mobile column under [[Brigadier-General Dartnell]] in the Eastern [[South African Republic|Transvaal]] which carried out a [[scorched earth]] campaign.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=75}}\n\nMore action was seen by the [[mounted infantry]] [[Company (military unit)|company]] of the regiment that had been formed on arrival in South Africa. In January 1900 [[Frederick Roberts, 1st Earl Roberts|Lord Roberts]], commander of the British forces in South Africa, ordered that every infantry battalion in South Africa was to raise a company of mounted infantry. These companies were to be detached from their parent units and operate as part of eight independent mounted infantry battalions.{{sfn|Badsey|2008|p=97}} The North Staffords company thus formed became part of the 8th Battalion, Mounted Infantry. This unit was involved in the pursuit of [[Koos de la Rey]] and was present when he was captured at [[Wildfontein]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=76}} The militia and volunteer battalions also saw service in the Second Boer War. The 4th Battalion was deployed in the Cape Colony and later the [[Bechuanaland Protectorate]] before being replaced by the 3rd Battalion.{{sfn|Cook|1970|pp=77\u201378}} Additionally, the two volunteer companies which formed from the 1st and 2nd Volunteer battalions served alongside the 2nd Battalion at various times.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=78}} As a result of these contributions and those of the two regular battalions, the regiment was awarded the \"South Africa 1900\u20131902\" battle honour.{{sfn|Rodger|2003|p=69}}\n\nAt the war's end in June 1902, the 2nd battalion returned to England on the SS ''Galeka'' in October that year,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Army in South Africa - Troops returning home| day_of_week=Wednesday |date=24 September 1902 |page_number=7 |issue=36881}}</ref> but the home posting was brief. In the following year, it returned to India, remaining there until 1919.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=128}}\n\n===Meeting in India===\nThe 1st Battalion was stationed in India from 1897 until 1903. The battalion was divided between barracks in [[Jhansi]] and [[Nowgong, Chhatarpur|Nowgong]] until late 1902, when it was reunited at [[Bombay]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence - The Army in India|day_of_week=Saturday |date=11 October 1902 |page_number=12 |issue=36896| }}</ref> The following year, the 1st and 2nd Battalions met for the first time, and no fewer than 590 men from the 1st Battalion were transferred to the 2nd Battalion.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=71}} Thus 1st Battalion was reduced to a small cadre, which served for nine years upon its return to Lichfield and other stations in England, before moving to [[Buttevant]] in Ireland in 1912.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1914-1918.net/nstaffs.htm|title=The North Staffordshire Regiment|author=Chris Baker|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==First World War (1914\u20131918)==\nThe North Staffordshire Regiment was heavily committed to the fighting during the First World War, and over the course of the conflict, was expanded to 18 battalions, some by duplication of the Territorial Force battalions and others, labelled \"service\" battalions raised as part of [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener's]] [[Kitchener's Army|New Army]]. These battalions saw service in a number of theatres including on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]], at [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli]], in the [[Middle Eastern theatre of World War I|Middle East]], and [[World War I#Southern theatres|India]].{{sfn|Chappell|2009|loc=[http://warpath.orbat.com/regts/n_staffs.htm Prince of Wales's (North Staffordshire Regiment)]}} The following list details the involvement of these battalions:\n\n* 1st Battalion \u2013 served in France from September 1914 until November 1918;\n* 2nd Battalion \u2013 served in India throughout the war;\n* 3rd (Reserve) Battalion \u2013 operated as a training battalion in the United Kingdom throughout the war;\n* 4th (Extra Reserve) Battalion \u2013 garrison battalion in Guernsey 1914\u20131916. Returned to United Kingdom in 1916. Served in France 1917\u20131918;\n* 1/5th Battalion Territorial Force (TF) \u2013 mobilised in 1914, and served in France from 1915 to 1918;\n* 1/6th Battalion TF \u2013 mobilised in 1914, served in France from 1915 to 1918;\n* 2/5th Battalion TF \u2013 formed in 1914, moved to Ireland in 1916 where it was involved in the [[Easter Rising]], served in France 1917\u20131918. Merged with 1/5th Battalion in February 1918;\n* 2/6th Battalion TF \u2013 formed in 1914, moved to Ireland in 1916 where it was involved in the Easter Rising, served in France 1917\u20131918. Merged with 1/6th Battalion in July 1918;\n* 3/5th Battalion TF \u2013 formed in 1915. Renamed 5th (Reserve) Battalion in April 1916. Served as a training battalion in England 1915\u20131918;\n* 3/6th Battalion TF \u2013 formed in 1915. Renamed 6th (Reserve) Battalion in April 1916. Merged with 5th (Reserve) Battalion in September 1916;\n* 7th (Service) Battalion \u2013 formed in 1914. Took part in Gallipoli Campaign July 1915 \u2013 January 1916. Evacuated to Egypt. Served in Mesopotamia from February 1916. From July 1918 were part of North Persia Force (Dunsterforce) and ended the war in Baku, Azerbaijan.\n* 8th (Service) Battalion \u2013 formed in 1914. Served in France 1915\u20131918;\n* 9th (Service) Battalion (Pioneers) \u2013 formed as a service battalion in 1914. Became a [[Pioneer (military)|pioneer]] battalion in 1915. Served in France and Belgium 1915\u20131919;\n* 10th (Reserve) Battalion \u2013 formed as a service battalion in 1914. Became a reserve battalion in 1915. Renamed as 3rd Training Reserve Battalion of 1st Reserve Brigade in 1916;\n* 11th (Reserve) Battalion \u2013 formed as a service battalion in 1914. Became a reserve battalion in 1915. Renamed as 4th Training Reserve Battalion of 1st Reserve Brigade in 1916;\n* 12th (Service) Battalion \u2013 formed 1918 in France from 11th Garrison Guard Battalion. Renamed as a service battalion and continued to serve in France;\n* 1st (Garrison) Battalion \u2013 formed in 1916. Served in France 1916\u20131918. Renamed 13th (Garrison) Battalion in July 1918;\n* 2nd (Home Service Garrison) Battalion \u2013 formed in 1916. Became 17th Battalion [[Royal Defence Corps]] in 1917.{{sfn|Chappell|2009|loc=[http://warpath.orbat.com/regts/n_staffs.htm Prince of Wales's (North Staffordshire Regiment)]}}\n\nThe numbering of the [[Territorial Force]] battalions was laid down by [[War Office]] instructions issued in 1914 and 1915. On joining the Territorial Force men were asked if they would serve overseas (foreign service) or just volunteered for service in the United Kingdom (home service) and their service records amended accordingly. At the declaration of war all Territorial battalions were mobilised and on 15 August 1914 the War Office issued instructions for those men who had volunteered for foreign service to be separated out into what were called first line battalions. Home service men were placed in second line battalions. Thus there would now be a first line 5th Battalion and a second line 5th Battalion. On 24 November 1914, as the first line battalions began to go overseas, additional instructions were issued allowing the raising of a third line battalion once the first line battalion was on foreign service. In January 1915 these designations were simplified and the battalions called the 1/5th, 2/5th and 3/5th battalions respectively.{{sfn|Baker|2009|loc=[http://www.1914-1918.net/tf.htm The Territorial Force 1914\u20131918]}}{{sfn|Beckett|1991|p=229}}\n\nThe battalions that served in France took part in many of the major actions of the war including the 1915 [[Battle of Neuve Chapelle]], the 1915 [[Battle of Loos]], the [[Battle of the Somme]] in 1916, the [[Battle of Passchendaele|Third Battle of Ypres]] in 1917 and the [[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Battle of Amiens]] in 1918.{{sfn|Cook|1970|loc=Chapter 10}}\n\n[[File:North Staffs 1 Bn officers 1914.jpg|thumb|300px|Officers of the 1st Battalion, photographed in Cambridge in August 1914, shortly before embarking for France on 8 September. Of those who sailed, only five would still be with the battalion by the end of January 1915, most of the remainder having been killed or wounded.{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|p=15}} Those pictured include Lieut.-Colonel V. W. de Falbe, D.S.O., Battalion Commanding Officer (seated row, centre); and junior subaltern 2nd Lieut. [[Vyvyan Pope]], who later commanded the battalion June 1917\u2013March 1918 (back row, third from left).]]\n\n===Military service===\n\n;1st Battalion\n\nThe 1st Battalion went to France in September 1914 as part of [[17th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|17th Brigade]] in [[6th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|6th Division]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=81}} It took part in the [[First Battle of Ypres]] being based in the Armenti\u00e8res sector on the southern flank of the battle.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=82}}{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=5\u201312}} In December 1914 it was in trenches in the [[Rue-du-Bois]] area (near [[Fleurbaix]]), and participated in the [[Christmas truce]], where British and [[German Army (German Empire)|German]] soldiers fraternised in [[no man's land]].{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=13\u201315}}{{sfn|Musgrove Knibb|2014|pp=72\u201380|ps=: an eye-witness account of the truce in a letter home by Captain R.J. Armes.}}\n\nIn March 1915 it carried out a successful action in the [[Battle of Neuve Chapelle]], capturing the village of L'Epinette.{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=16\u201318}}\n\nIn October 1915 17th Brigade was exchanged with [[71st Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|71st Brigade]] of [[24th Division (United Kingdom)|24th Division]], as part of an official policy of mixing [[Standing army|Regular]] with [[Kitchener's Army|New Army]] units. Immediately on joining 24th Division, the battalion was moved to [[72nd Brigade (United Kingdom)|72nd Brigade]] within the same division. It was to remain part of this formation until the end of the war.{{sfn|Chappell|2009|loc=[http://warpath.orbat.com/divs/24_div.htm 24th Division]}}\n\nIn April and June 1916 the battalion suffered casualties of well over 500 in [[Gas attacks at Wulverghem|two serious gas attacks]], on both occasions when in trenches north of [[Wulverghem]] (near [[Mesen|Messines]]).{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=28\u201332, 113}}\n\nIn August\u2013September 1916, the 24th Division participated in the [[Battle of the Somme]]. The 1st Battalion was engaged in the fighting around [[Battle of Guillemont|Guillemont]] and later the defence of [[Battle of Delville Wood|Delville Wood]], suffering a total of more than 350 casualties.{{sfn|Cook|1970|pp=84\u201387}}{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=34\u201344, 113}}\n\nIn June 1917, the battalion was involved (and suffered over 150 casualties) in the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|assault on Messines Ridge]], one of the most successful British offensives of the war.{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=50\u201351, 113}} This battle formed a prelude to the [[Battle of Passchendaele|Third Battle of Ypres]], when the battalion took part in the initial assault on 31 July 1917. Its objectives were to capture the German frontline trench called Jehovah trench, the second line trench called Jordan trench and the remains of Bulgar Wood. These three objectives were {{convert|1000|yards|m}}, {{convert|1500|yards|m}} and {{convert|1750|yards|m}} from the British front line. The battalion managed to capture both trenches and a platoon reached Bulgar Wood before events around them forced a retreat from Bulgar Wood and Jordan trench. The battalion dug in on the Jehovah trench line having lost 11 officers and 258 other ranks as casualties, almost 50% of the battalion strength.{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=54\u201361, 113}}{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=88\u201389}}{{sfn|Tanner|2017}} After the war, the anniversary of this attack became the main Regimental Day.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=89}}\n\nOn 21 March 1918, the 1st Battalion was in front-line trenches near [[St. Quentin]] when the German Army launched [[Operation Michael]], the opening attack in their [[Spring Offensive]]. The battalion was virtually wiped out, losing 19 officers and 662 men in the attack itself and the withdrawal which followed.{{sfn|Cook|1970|pp=90\u201392}}{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=68\u201383}} The battalion was subsequently re-formed, and in the last weeks of the war in October 1918 took part in the [[Pursuit to the Selle|Battle of the Selle]], in which it suffered nearly 200 casualties.{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=91\u201394, 114}}\n\n[[File:Riqueval Bridge 1918.jpg|thumb|left|300px|137th Brigade (including 1/6th Battalion North Staffs) at the Riqueval Bridge on the St Quentin Canal, October 1918]]\n\n;2nd Battalion\n\nThe 2nd Battalion was one of only eight regular battalions of the British Army to remain in India throughout the war.{{sfn|Green|2019|p=6}} It took part in operations on the [[North-West Frontier Province (1901\u20131955)|North West Frontier]] in 1915, as a result of which the regiment was awarded the battle honour \"North West Frontier, India, 1915\".{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=99\u2013101, 105}} Amusingly, the [[commanding officer]] at this time was [[Major]] Fox and the [[adjutant]] [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] Squirell.{{sfn|War Diary|1915}} Although it was a Regular Army battalion, it received very few replacements during the war. From a pre-war establishment strength of a HQ plus eight companies,{{sfn|Historical Record|1908}} after the 1915 North West Frontier campaign the battalion comprised only a HQ company and four rifle companies.{{sfn|War Diary|1915}} By 1919 the strength of the regiment was reduced by a third compared to the pre-war establishment with 20 officers and 538 enlisted men on the regimental roll.{{sfn|Green|2019|p=28\u201329}} Over 60% of the enlisted men had joined the battalion since the 1915 campaign and only five officers fought in both the 1915 campaign and the Third Afghan War in 1919.{{sfn|Green|2019|p=28\u201329}}\n\n;1/5th and 1/6th Battalions\n\nThe [[Staffordshire Rangers|1/5th]] and 1/6th battalions arrived in France in February 1915 as part of [[Staffordshire Brigade|137th (Staffordshire) Brigade]] of [[46th (North Midland) Division]].{{sfn|Chappell|2009|loc=[http://warpath.orbat.com/divs/46_div.htm 46th Division]}} Among the first [[Territorial Force]] units to go to France, these two battalions took part in the 1915 [[Battle of Loos]], especially the battles around the [[Hohenzollern Redoubt]] in 1915, and at Gommecourt on the northern flank of the Battle of the Somme.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=92}}\n\nBy September 1918 the 1/5th Battalion had been reduced to a [[Cadre (military)|cadre]]{{sfn|Chappell|2009|loc=[http://warpath.orbat.com/divs/59_div.htm 59th Division]}} and had been transferred away from 46th Division. The 1/6th remained and with the rest of 137th Brigade took part in the storming of the [[Battle of St. Quentin Canal|St Quentin Canal]].{{sfn|Chappell|2009|loc=[http://warpath.orbat.com/divs/59_div.htm 59th Division]}}{{sfn|Rickard|2007|loc=[http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_cambrai_st_quentin.html Battle of Cambrai-St. Quentin, 27 September-9 October 1918]}} It was a company of the  1/6th Battalion, led by acting Captain A. H. Charlton, that seized the Riqueval Bridge over the St Quentin Canal on 29 September before the Germans could fire the explosive charges, an action for which Charlton was decorated with the [[Distinguished Service Order]].<ref name=LG31583>{{London Gazette |issue=31583 |supp=y |page=12221 |date=3 October 1919 }}</ref>\n\n;12th Battalion\n\nThe 12th Battalion formed part of [[40th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|40th Division]] and served in France on the River Lys during the advance in Flanders (18 August to 6 September 1918) and the [[Fifth Battle of Ypres]], and in France and Belgium during the final weeks of the war.{{sfn|Chappell|2009|loc=[http://warpath.orbat.com/divs/40_div.htm 40th Division]}}\n\n===Awards and decorations===\nAltogether, the regiment was awarded 52 battle honours, but it was ruled that only ten could be carried on the [[Colours, standards and guidons#United Kingdom|colours]].{{sfn|Swinson|1972|p=241}}\n\n====Victoria Crosses====\nFour [[Victoria Cross]]es were awarded to men of the North Staffordshire Regiment during World War I:\n* [[Sergeant]] [[John Carmichael (VC)|John Carmichael]], 9th Battalion; for gallantry on 8 September 1917 during the [[Battle of Passchendaele|Third Battle of Ypres]];<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30338 |supp=y|page=10677|date=16 October 1917}}</ref>\n* [[Lance corporal|Lance-Corporal]] [[William Harold Coltman]], 1/6th Battalion; for gallantry on the nights of 3 & 4 October 1918 near [[Sequehart]], France;<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31108 |supp=y|page=308|date=3 January 1919}}</ref>\n* Acting [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Edward Elers Delaval Henderson]], 7th Battalion (attached 9th Battalion [[Royal Warwickshire Regiment]]); for gallantry on 25 January 1917 in [[Mesopotamia]]. This award was made posthumously;<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30122 |supp=y|page=5701|date=8 June 1917}}</ref>\n* Lance-Corporal [[John Thomas (VC)|John Thomas]], 2/5th Battalion for gallantry on 30 November 1917 during the [[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Battle of Cambrai]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30523 |supp=y|page=2005|date=13 February 1918}}</ref>\n\n===Reputation for profanity===\nEven by the standards of the British Army, the Regiment (and the 1st Battalion in particular) seems to have gained a reputation during the First World War for [[profanity|profane language]]. When the 1st Battalion was relieved in the front line following its defence of [[Battle of Delville Wood|Delville Wood]] in September 1916, one of the advanced posts was missed out by mistake. The [[Lance corporal|Lance-Corporal]] in command, suspecting something was amiss, sent a man back to the front-line trench to investigate. The soldier realised he was at some risk of being shot by his own side, and so \"when he had crawled within shouting distance he enquired politely but firmly what \u2014\u2014 bastards were holding that \u2014\u2014 trench. The 9th [[East Surrey Regiment|East Surreys]], who were the troops thus addressed, recognised the North Stafford idiom and let him in unhurt\".{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|p=42}} Bernard Martin, who served as a [[Second lieutenant|2nd Lieutenant]] with the 1st Battalion, records another incident which probably took place in 1917, when (very unusually) the battalion was addressed at a [[church parade]] by a [[General officer|general]], who railed against \"the disgusting word many of you utter every time you speak. ... I tell you again this indecent word is not to be used any longer. It is so common amongst you that it has become the shameful nickname by which your battalion is known throughout my Division\". As the parade ended, one soldier was heard to ask, \"What was that [[bugger]] gassing about?\"; to which another replied, \"Buggered if I know, I was having a kip. Where's the old bugger gone now?\".{{sfn|Martin|1987|pp=132\u2013133|ps=: Martin names the general as \"General Pawson\", but this appears to be a pseudonym.}}\n\n==Interwar years (1918\u20131939)==\nThe 1st Battalion was posted to [[the Curragh]], Ireland after the armistice, becoming involved in the [[Irish War of Independence]] until 1922, when it moved to [[Gibraltar]]. In the following year it was moved to [[Thrace]], where it played a [[peace-keeping]] role in the conflict between Greek and Turkish forces. In 1923 it moved to India and remained in the Far East until 1948.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=156}}\n\nThe 2nd Battalion was stationed in India in 1919 when Afghan forces crossed the border and occupied some Indian territory, sparking the brief [[Third Anglo-Afghan War]]. During this conflict, the battalion was involved very early on, firstly in the investing of [[Peshawar|Peshawar City]], where Afghan sympathisers were mooting a holy war{{sfn|Third Afghan War 1919 Official Account|1926|p=30}} and on 11 May 1919 when they were involved in a bayonet charge on the Afghan forces at Bagh, near Landi Kotal.{{sfn|History of the 1st & 2nd Battalions The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales'), 1914\u20131923|1932|pp=102\u2013104}}{{sfn|Barthorp|2002|p=152}}{{sfn|Third Afghan War 1919 Official Account|1926|pp=31\u201335}} For their involvement, the regiment received the battle honour \"Afghanistan NWF 1919\".{{sfn|Rodger|2003|p=208}} The battalion returned to England via Egypt and the Sudan in 1921, and was quickly redeployed to Ireland. On the establishment of the [[Irish Free State]] in 1922, it returned to the regimental depot at [[Lichfield]]. Until 1939, it spent time in \"home stations\". Apart from England, this included service in [[Gibraltar]] from 1930 to 1932 and a year in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] in 1936\u20137.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=128}}\n\nThe 3rd and 4th (Special Reserve) Battalions were placed in suspended animation in 1921, finally being disbanded in 1953.{{sfn|Bellis|2003|p=116}}\n\nThe Territorial Force was reconstituted as the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]] in 1920, and the 5th and 6th battalions were reformed, still with the [[Staffordshire Brigade|137th (Staffordshire) Brigade]] of [[46th (North Midland) Division]]. In 1936, the 5th Battalion was converted to an anti-aircraft searchlight unit of the [[Royal Engineers]] as [[Staffordshire Rangers#Interwar years|41st (North Staffordshire Regiment) Anti-Aircraft Battalion]] while remaining 'part of the corps of the North Staffordshire Regiment'.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=105}} It was transferred to the Royal Artillery in August 1940 as the 41st (5th North Staffordshire) Searchlight Regiment TA.{{sfn|Palmer|2010|p=6}} In the same year the remaining 6th Battalion was transferred to [[166th (South Lancashire) Brigade|166th Infantry Brigade]], [[55th (West Lancashire) Infantry Division]] after the HQ of the 46th Division became [[2nd Anti-Aircraft Division (United Kingdom)|2nd Anti-Aircraft Division]]. Throughout the spring and summer of 1939, due to the increasing threat posed by [[Nazi Germany]], the size of the Territorial Army was doubled, and the 6th Battalion formed a duplicate 7th Battalion.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=118}}\n\nIn 1921, the regimental title was altered to '''The North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales's)'''.<ref>Army Order 509/1920</ref> In 1937, the black facings formerly worn by the 64th Foot were restored, replacing the white colour that had been imposed on all non-royal English regiments in 1881.<ref>G.O. 41/1881 1 May 1881 amended by G.O.70/1881 1 July 1881. ''\"X. The facings, and the Officers lace will be the same for all regiments belonging to the same Country (Royal and Rifle Regiments excepted), and will as follows: English Regiments: Facings \u2013 White, Pattern of Lace \u2013 Rose\"''</ref>{{sfn|Regimental customs and traditions of the Mercian Regiment|2009|p=2}}\n\nThe [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]] renamed one of their [[LMS Royal Scot Class#Details|Royal Scot]] class locomotives, number 6141 (formerly ''Caledonian''), after the regiment.{{sfn|Rowledge|1989|p=64}}\n\n==Second World War (1939\u20131945)==\nIn September 1939, the North Staffordshire Regiment consisted of two [[Standing army|Regular]] and two [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial]] battalions \u2013 the 1st and 2nd Regular and the 6th and 7th Territorials.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=118}} Following the outbreak of the [[World War II|Second World War]] on 3 September 1939, the regiment was expanded as it had been during the First World War. This expansion, however, was limited this time only to the addition of two more battalions \u2013 the 8th and 9th battalions, of which both were raised in 1940 but later converted to other roles.{{sfn|The brief history of the Staffordshire Regiment, part 2|2009|p=2}}{{sfn|Bellis|2003|p=117}} The roles of the two regular battalions were reversed this time, with the 1st Battalion serving in [[British Raj|India]] and [[Burma Campaign|Burma]] throughout the war, while the 2nd Battalion remained in [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italy]] and [[North African Campaign|North Africa]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=110}}\n\nThe North Staffordshire Regiment was awarded 22 battle honours for the Second World War but, as at the end of the First World War, only 10 could be displayed on the colours.{{sfn|Swinson|1972|p=241}}\n\n===Regular Army===\nThe 1st Battalion was in British India on the outbreak of the Second World War and saw no action until 1942, when one company that was stationed on the [[Andaman Islands]] were involved in the defence of the islands during the [[Invasion and occupation of the Andaman Islands during World War II|Japanese invasion]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=117}} In 1943, the battalion served for six months in Burma, with the [[36th Indian Infantry Brigade]], part of the [[26th Infantry Division (India)|26th Indian Infantry Division]], before being withdrawn to India again.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=117}} For the rest of the war, the battalion was employed mainly on [[internal security]] duties and saw no further action.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=117}}\n\n[[File:The British Army in France 1940 F2105.jpg|thumb|right|Troops of the 2nd Battalion on exercise with the Royal Tank Regiment in France, 1940]]\n\nThe 2nd Battalion, under the command of [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant Colonel]] Donald Butterworth, was sent to France shortly after the outbreak of war in September 1939 as part of the [[2nd Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|2nd Infantry Brigade]] (alongside the 1st [[Loyal Regiment (North Lancashire)|Loyal Regiment]] and 1st [[Gordon Highlanders]]), [[1st Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|1st Infantry Division]] and was part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] (BEF), and was involved in the battles of [[Battle of France|France]] and [[Battle of Belgium|Belgium]] before eventually being [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuated from Dunkirk]] on 1 June 1940.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=109}} Following that, the 2nd Battalion spent years on home defence in the United Kingdom preparing for a possible [[Operation Sea Lion|German invasion of England]] which never arrived. The battalion remained in the United Kingdom until 1943 when, still as part of 1st Infantry Division, it sailed to North Africa and took part in the [[Tunisia Campaign|campaign in Tunisia]], [[First Army (United Kingdom)|British First Army]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=110}} The battalion did not participate in the [[Allied invasion of Sicily|invasion of Sicily]] or the [[Allied invasion of Italy|initial invasion of Italy]] but was one of the lead units in the [[Battle of Anzio|Anzio landings]] in January 1944, under command of [[United States Army North|US Fifth Army]], where they suffered extremely heavy casualties.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=112}} On 7 February the battalion suffered 323 casualties attempting to capture Buonriposo Ridge which they captured but were forced to surrender the ridge after expending their ammunition.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=113}} By May, following [[Operation Diadem]], the battalion had absorbed eight drafts of replacements.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=112}} Now fighting as part of the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|British Eighth Army]], the 2nd Battalion continued to serve in Italy, fighting around the [[Gothic Line]], until January 1945 when the battalion and the rest of 1st Infantry Division were transferred to [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=117}}\n\n===Territorial Army===\nThe [[Staffordshire Rangers|41st (5th North Staffordshire Regiment) Searchlight Regiment, Royal Engineers]], previously the 5th North Staffords, served in [[Anti-Aircraft Command]] as part of the air defence of the Midlands from 1939 to 1944. The regiment became the first complete searchlight regiment to land in Normandy after the [[Normandy landings|D-Day landings of 6 June 1944]]. It served with [[21st Army Group]], as part of [[31st (North Midland) Anti-Aircraft Brigade]], until the end of the war in Europe and then undertook garrison duty in [[Lower Saxony]].<ref>41 AA Bn RE/41 SL Rgt RA War Diaries, August 1939\u2013December 1945, [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives (TNA), Kew]] files WO 166/3059, WO 166/7792, WO 166/11502, WO 166/14873, WO 171/1203, WO 171/5089.</ref>\n\nThe two Territorial battalions formed part of [[176th (2/1st Staffordshire) Brigade|176th Infantry Brigade]] (which included both the 6th and 7th North Staffords and the 7th [[South Staffordshire Regiment|South Staffords]]) of [[59th (Staffordshire) Infantry Division]]. The division trained in the United Kingdom for many years until it [[Invasion of Normandy|landed in Normandy]] in June 1944 as part of [[Operation Overlord]] where they fought in the [[Battle for Caen]] and gained an excellent reputation during [[Operation Charnwood]] and the [[Second Battle of the Odon]].{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=117}} However, only the 6th Battalion landed in France as the 7th Battalion had been transferred elsewhere in 1942, being replaced in the 176th Brigade by the 7th [[Royal Norfolk Regiment|Royal Norfolks]]. The 6th Battalion had been in France for less than two months when, in August 1944, along with other infantry units of 59th Division, it was broken up to supply replacements to other British units, due to a severe shortage of infantry replacements throughout the Army at the time.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=118}} The 7th Battalion, upon leaving 59th Division, served with the [[207th Independent Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|207th]] and [[228th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|228th Infantry]] brigades in the [[Orkney]] and [[Shetland]] islands in 1943\u20131945, and later the [[25th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|25th Brigade]], before being transferred in 1945 as an administrative unit in the [[183rd (2nd Gloucester and Worcester) Brigade|183rd Brigade]] within the [[61st Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|61st Infantry Division]] and, in 1945 after the war in Europe was over, was preparing for a move to the [[Far East]] to fight the Japanese but they surrendered before the division arrived.{{sfn|The Staffords in WWII|(undated)|p=34}} The battalion was disbanded after the war in 1947.{{sfn|The Staffords in WWII|(undated)|p=34}}\n\n===Hostilities-only===\nThe 8th Battalion was initially raised as a training battalion in 1940 and was assigned to the [[205th Independent Infantry Brigade (Home)]] and was mainly concerned in home defence duties. The 8th Battalion was transferred to the [[Royal Artillery]] in March 1942 and converted to the [[180th Field Regiment, Royal Artillery|180th Field Regiment]].{{sfn|Heath|2005|loc=[http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/stories/12/a5179412.shtml A right military cock-up]}} The regiment served with the [[48th (South Midland) Division|48th Infantry (Reserve) Division]] in a training role until it was disbanded in August 1944.{{sfn|Evans|2008|loc=[http://members.tripod.com/~nigelef/regtsumm.htm Field artillery formations and regiments of the Royal Artillery in World War 2]}}\n\nThe 9th Battalion was, like the 8th Battalion, also initially raised as a training battalion, and was assigned to the [[224th Brigade (United Kingdom)|224th Independent Infantry Brigade (Home)]]. The 9th Battalion was transferred to the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] in December 1941, becoming [[154th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]], retaining their North Staffords cap badge on the black beret of the Royal Armoured Corps, as did all other infantry units converted in this way. The regiment was assigned to [[36th Tank Brigade (United Kingdom)|36th Army Tank Brigade]] alongside RAC regiments converted from infantry battalions.{{sfn|Forty|1998|p=51}}{{sfn|Bellis|2003|p=117}}{{sfn|The Staffords in WWII|(undated)|p=34}} However, the regiment was disbanded in July 1943.{{sfn|Bellis|2003|p=35}}\n\n==Postwar service (1945\u20131959)==\nFollowing the [[independence of India]] in 1947, all infantry regiments in the British Army were reduced to a single regular battalion. Accordingly, the 1st Battalion left India to take part in a ceremony officially amalgamating with the 2nd Battalion in Egypt in 1948.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=120}}  The new 1st Battalion remained in Egypt until 1950, when it returned to the depot in Staffordshire. A year later, the battalion was posted to the disputed port city of [[Trieste]]. In 1953, the battalion was transferred to [[South Korea|Korea]], where they were stationed on garrison duties as part of the [[United Nations]] force established at the end of the [[Korean War]]. In 1954, it moved to Hong Kong, where the regiment's 200th anniversary was celebrated in 1956.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=129}}\n\n==Amalgamation==\nIn July 1957, a [[1957 Defence White Paper|defence review]] was announced, which resulted in the amalgamation of the North Staffordshire Regiment with the [[South Staffordshire Regiment]], with the new regiment becoming part of the new administrative [[Mercian Brigade]]. The amalgamation of the 1st Battalions of the two regiments took place on 31 January 1959 at [[Minden, Germany]], to form the 1st Battalion, '''[[Staffordshire Regiment|Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales's)]]'''.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=122}}\n\nIn 1947, 41 Searchlight Regiment was reformed in the Territorial Army as 576 (5th Bn, The North Staffordshire Regiment) Searchlight Regiment RA (TA), later becoming 576 Light Anti-Aircraft/Searchlight Regiment (576 LAA/SL). When AA Command was disbanded in 1955 and the number of air defence units reduced, 576 LAA/SL Regiment was amalgamated with [[Lancashire Hussars|349 (Lancashire Yeomanry) LAA]] and [[93rd Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|493 Heavy Anti-Aircraft]] Regiments as 441 LAA/SL Regiment.{{sfn|Litchfield|1992|p=32}}\n\nThe 6th Battalion continued as a Territorial unit of the new regiment without a change of title. In 1961, it merged with the 441st Light Anti Aircraft Regiment, [[Royal Artillery]], the successor to the 5th North Staffords, to become the 5th/6th Battalion.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=124}} The combined battalion was abolished in 1967 on the creation of the [[Territorial and Army Volunteer Reserve]] in 1967.{{sfn|Cook|1970|p=124}}\n\nThe Staffordshire Regiment only had a separate existence from 1959\u20132007. As part of the reforms proposed in the 2003 Defence White Paper, ''[[Delivering Security in a Changing World]]'', the regiment was merged with the [[Cheshire Regiment]] and the [[Worcestershire and Sherwood Foresters|Worcestershire and Sherwood Foresters Regiment]] to form the [[Mercian Regiment]]. The amalgamation took place on 1 September 2007 in Tamworth Castle Grounds, when the Staffordshire Regiment became the 3rd Battalion, the Mercian Regiment. Subsequently, in 2014, The Mercian Regiment reduced its number of regular battalions from three to two, with the 3rd Battalion being disbanded and the personnel being redeployed into the 1st and 2nd Battalions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-27988491 |title=Mercian Regiment: Final marches for disbanded battalion |date=24 June 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2015 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Regimental museum==\nThe [[Staffordshire Regiment Museum]] is based at [[Whittington Barracks]] near [[Lichfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staffordshireregimentmuseum.com/ |title=No frills but plenty of guts|publisher=The Staffordshire Regiment Museum|accessdate= 22 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Battle honours==\nThe following lists all battle honours awarded to the Regiment or inherited by the regiment from the 64th Foot and 98th Foot.{{sfn|Cook|1970|loc=various}}\n\nPrior to 1914 all battle honours awarded to a unit were displayed upon the colours.{{sfn|Rodger|2003|p=9}} However the number of battle honours awarded during the First World War was such that it was ordered that no more than 24 honours were to be carried on the colours, of which no more than 10 were to be honours relating to the First World War.<ref>Army Order 338/1922 paragraph 1(d).</ref>  Similarly, following the Second World War it was ordered that up to 10 honours relating to that conflict could be displayed on the colours, in addition to honours already carried.<ref>Army Council Instruction 58/1956 paragraph 5.</ref> The choice of the honours to be displayed were at the discretion of regimental committees. The honours chosen by the North Staffordshire Regiment to be carried on the colours are shown in capitals in the following list.{{sfn|Swinson|1972|p=241}}\n\n===Honours awarded to the 64th Foot===\n* [[Invasion of Guadeloupe (1759)|GUADALOUPE 1759]]\n* [[Battle of Martinique (1794)|MARTINIQUE 1794]]\n* [[History of Saint Lucia#19th century|ST LUCIA 1803]]\n* [[History of Suriname#Slavery and emancipation|SURINAM]]\n* [[Anglo-Persian War|RESHIRE]]\n* [[Anglo-Persian War|BUSHIRE]]\n* [[Anglo-Persian War|KOOSH-AB]]\n* [[Persia 1856-57 (Battle honour)|PERSIA]]\n* [[Siege of Lucknow#Second relief|LUCKNOW]]\n\n===Honours awarded to the 98th Foot===\n* [[First Opium War#War|The DRAGON superscribed CHINA]]\n* [[First Anglo-Sikh War|PUNJAUB]]\n\n===1881\u20131914===\n* [[Mahdist War#Return of the British|HAFIR]]\n* [[Second Boer War|SOUTH AFRICA 1900\u20131902]]\n\n===1914\u20131919===\n{{Colbegin|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Race to the Sea|ARMENTIERES 1914]]\n* [[Battle of the Somme|SOMME 1916]], [[Operation Michael|1918]]\n* [[Arras 1917|ARRAS 1917]]\n* [[Battle of Messines (1917)|MESSINES 1917]], [[Battle of the Lys (1918)#Battle of Messines|1918]]\n* [[Ypres 1917|YPRES]], [[Fifth Battle of Ypres|1918]]\n* [[Battle of St. Quentin Canal|ST. QUENTIN CANAL]]\n* [[Battle of Cambrai (1918)|SELLE]]\n* [[Battle of Sari Bair|SARI BAIR]]\n* [[Second Battle of Kut|KUT AL AMARA 1917]]\n* [[North-West Frontier (military history)|NORTH-WEST FRONTIER INDIA 1915]]\n* [[Third Afghan War|AFGHANISTAN NWF 1919]]\n* [[First Battle of the Aisne|Aisne 1914]], [[Third Battle of the Aisne|1918]]\n* [[Battle of Loos|Loos]]\n* [[Battle of Albert (1916)|Albert 1916]], [[Second Battle of the Somme (1918)|1918]]\n* [[Battle of Bazentin Ridge|Bazentin]]\n* [[Battle of Delville Wood|Delville Wood]]\n* [[Battle of Pozi\u00e8res|Pozi\u00e8res]]\n* [[Battle of Guillemont|Guillemont]]\n* [[Battle of the Ancre Heights|Ancre Heights]]\n* [[Battle of the Ancre|Ancre 1916]]\n* [[First Battle of the Scarpe|Scarpe 1917]]\n* [[Battle of Arleux|Arleux]]\n* [[Battle of Pilckem Ridge|Pilckem]]\n* [[Battle of Langemarck (1917)|Langemarck 1917]]\n* [[Battle of the Menin Road Ridge|Menin Road]]\n* [[Battle of Polygon Wood|Polygon Wood]]\n* [[Battle of Broodseinde|Broodseinde]]\n* [[Battle of Poelcappelle|Poelcapelle]]\n* [[Passchendaele (Battle honour)|Passchendaele]]\n* [[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Cambrai 1917]], [[Battle of Cambrai (1918)|1918]]\n* [[Battle of St. Quentin Canal|St Quentin]]\n* [[Second Battle of the Somme (1918)|Bapaume 1918]]\n* [[Second Battle of the Somme (1918)|Rosi\u00e8res]]\n* [[Second Battle of the Somme (1918)|Avre]]\n* [[Battle of the Lys (1918)|Lys]]\n* [[Battle of the Lys (1918)|Bailleul]]\n* [[Battle of Kemmel Ridge|Kemmel]]\n* [[Hindenburg Line]]\n* [[Battle of Havrincourt|Havrincourt]]\n* [[Battle of the Canal du Nord|Canal du Nord]]\n* [[Battle of St. Quentin Canal#Battle|Beau-revoir]]\n* [[Battle of Cambrai (1918)|Courtrai]]\n* [[Hundred Days Offensive#German retreat|Valenciennes]]\n* [[Battle of the Sambre (1918)|Sambre]]\n* [[Western Front (World War I)|France and Flanders 1914\u201318]]\n* [[Landing at Suvla Bay|Suvla]]\n* [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli 1915\u201316]]\n* [[Sinai and Palestine Campaign#Ottoman advance towards the Suez Canal|Egypt 1916]]\n* [[Battle of Wadi (1916)|Tigris 1916]]\n* [[Mesopotamian Campaign#1917|Baghdad]]\n* [[Mesopotamian campaign|Mesopotamia 1916\u201318]]\n* [[Battle of Baku|Baku]]\n* [[Persian Campaign|Persia 1918]]\n{{colend}}\n\n===1939\u20131945===\n{{Colbegin|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Battle of France#May: Fall Gelb, Low Countries and northern France|DYLE]]\n* [[Battle of France#May: Fall Gelb, Low Countries and northern France|YPRES-COMINES CANAL]]\n* [[Operation Charnwood|CAEN]]\n* [[Operation Bluecoat|BRIEUX BRIDGEHEAD]]\n* [[Tunisia Campaign|MEDJEZ PLAIN]]\n* [[Tunisia Campaign|NORTH AFRICA 1943]]\n* [[Operation Shingle|ANZIO]]\n* [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|ROME]]\n* [[Gothic Line#Central Front (5th Army)|MARRADI]]\n* [[Burma 1943|BURMA 1943]]\n* [[Battle of France|Defence of Escaut]]\n* [[Battles on the Orne River 1944|Orne]]\n* [[Operation Pomegranate|Noyers]]\n* [[Operation Bluecoat|Mont Pin\u00e7on]]\n* [[Battle of France|North-West Europe 1940]], 1944\n* [[Tunisia Campaign#Endgame|Djebel Kess Kiss]]\n* [[Tunisia Campaign#Endgame|Gueriat al Atach Ridge]]\n* [[Tunisia Campaign#Endgame|Gab Gab Gap]]\n* [[Operation Shingle#German counterattacks|Carroceto]]\n* [[Gothic Line|Advance to Tiber]]\n* [[Gothic Line]]\n* [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italy 1944\u20135]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Regimental Colonels==\nColonels of the Regiment were:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/064NStaf.htm |title=The  North Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales's) |publisher=regiments.org |accessdate=9 January 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070227171043/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/064NStaf.htm |archivedate=27 February 2007 }}</ref>\n*1881\u20131904: (1st Battalion only to 1891) Gen. [[Charles Algernon Lewis]]\n*1881\u20131891: (2nd Battalion) Gen. Sir [[Robert Percy Douglas]], Bt.\n*1904\u20131905: Gen. [[Francis Peyton]], CB \n*1905\u20131911: Gen. Sir [[George Digby Barker]], GCB\n*1911\u20131921: Maj-Gen. Thomas Francis Lloyd\n*1921\u20131936: Maj-Gen. Sir [[Arthur Hoskins|Arthur Reginald Hoskins]], KCB, CMG, DSO\n*1936\u20131945: Brig-Gen. Louis John Wyatt, DSO\n*1945\u20131955: Maj-Gen. [[William Donovan Stamer]], CB, CBE, DSO, MC\n*1955\u20131958: Brig. (Hon. Maj-Gen.) Charles Roger Alan Swynnerton, CB, DSO \n*1958\u20131959: Brig. [[Gerald Thubron|Gerald Ernest Thubron]], DSO, OBE\n\n''*1959 Regiment amalgamated with the [[South Staffordshire Regiment]] to form the [[Staffordshire Regiment]]''\n\n==Football==\n{{main|North Staffordshire Regiment F.C.}}\nThe 2nd Battalion's [[association football|football]] team was a member of the [[Irish Football League]] for three seasons, 1896\u201399, while the battalion was stationed at the [[Victoria Barracks, Belfast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nilhist.html |title= Northern Ireland \u2013 Final League Tables 1890\u20131998 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|North Staffordshire Regiment}}\n*[[:Category:North Staffordshire Regiment officers|Category:North Staffordshire Regiment officers]]\n*[[:Category:North Staffordshire Regiment soldiers|Category:North Staffordshire Regiment soldiers]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book \n| last      = Badsey \n| first     = Stephen \n| title     = Doctrine and Reform in the British Cavalry 1880\u20131918\n| url       = https://books.google.com/books?id=bdvBgUlO2qgC&lpg=PA153&ots=L_Tp_l1hs9&dq=mounted%20infantry%20boer%20war&pg=PA97 \n| accessdate= 5 July 2009 \n| series    = Birmingham Studies in First World War History \n|date=July 2008 \n| publisher = Ashgate Publishing \n| location  = Farnham, Surrey \n| isbn      = 978-0-7546-6467-3 \n| ref       = harv \n}}\n*{{cite web \n| first     = Chris\n| last      = Baker \n| title     = The Territorial Force 1914\u20131918 \n| url       = http://www.1914-1918.net/tf.htm \n| year      = 2009 \n| publisher = www.1914-1918.net \n| accessdate= 5 July 2009\n| ref       = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last      = Barthorp\n| first     = Michael\n| title     = Afghan Wars and the North West Frontier 1839\u20131947\n| edition   = 2nd\n| year      = 2002\n| publisher = Cassell\n| location  = London\n| isbn      = 0-304-36294-8\n| ref       = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last      = Becke\n| first     = Major A.F.\n| title     = History of the Great War: Order of Battle of Divisions, Part 2a: The Territorial Force Mounted Divisions and the 1st-Line Territorial Force Divisions (42\u201356)\n| publisher = Naval & Military Press\n| year  